ll,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lumbar plexus is a network of nerve fibres that supplies the skin and musculature of the lower limb. It is formed by the anterior rami of the L1-L4 spinal nerves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is formed by the anterior divisions of the L2-4 spinal nerves. It is part of the lumbar plexus and innervates the medial compartment of the thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESciatic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve is formed by the L4-S3 spinal nerves and is part of the sacral plexus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a branch of the sciatic nerve, originating from the L4-S3 spinal nerves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommon fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This is another branch of the sciatic nerve, also originating from the L4-S3 spinal nerves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior gluteal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve is formed by the L4-S1 spinal nerves and is part of the sacral plexus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The L2-4 spinal nerves contribute to the formation of the femoral and obturator nerves.","The lumbar plexus is formed by the anterior rami of the L1-L4 spinal nerves.","The femoral nerve innervates the anterior compartment of the thigh."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPear